member.summary: Indicates the algorithm that was used to sign the token, for example, "RS256"

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.ApplicationID
member.summary: Only present in v1.0 tokens. The application ID of the client using the token. The application can act as itself or on behalf of a user. The application ID typically represents an application object, but it can also represent a service principal object in Azure AD.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.ApplicationName
member.summary: Application name from registered Azure Application

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.Audience
member.summary: Identifies the intended recipient of the token. In access tokens, the audience is your app's Application ID, assigned to your app in the Azure portal. Your app should validate this value and reject the token if the value does not match.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.AuthenticationMethod
member.summary: Only present in v1.0 tokens. Identifies how the subject of the token was authenticated. See https://docs.microsoft.com/en-us/azure/active-directory/develop/access-tokens#the-amr-claim for more details. Microsoft identities can authenticate in a variety of ways, which may be relevant to your application. The amr claim is an array that can contain multiple items, such as ["mfa", "rsa", "pwd"], for an authentication that used both a password and the Authenticator app.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.ExpirationTime
member.summary: The "exp" (expiration time) claim identifies the expiration time on or after which the JWT must not be accepted for processing. It's important to note that a resource may reject the token before this time as well, such as when a change in authentication is required or a token revocation has been detected.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.GivenName
member.summary: Provides the first or given name of the user, as set on the user object.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.IssuedAt
member.summary: "Issued At" indicates when the authentication for this token occurred.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.Issuer
member.summary: Identifies the issuer, or "authorization server" that constructs and returns the token. It also identifies the tenant for which the user was authenticated. If the token was issued by the v2.0 endpoint, the URI ends in /v2.0. The GUID that indicates that the user is a consumer user from a Microsoft account is 9188040d-6c67-4c5b-b112-36a304b66dad.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.Name
member.summary: Provides a human-readable value that identifies the subject of the token. The value is not guaranteed to be unique, it is mutable, and it's designed to be used only for display purposes. The profile scope is required in order to receive this claim.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.NotBefore
member.summary: The "nbf" (not before) claim identifies the time before which the JWT must not be accepted for processing.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.OID
member.summary: he immutable identifier for an object in the Microsoft identity platform, in this case, a user account. It can also be used to perform authorization checks safely and as a key in database tables. This ID uniquely identifies the user across applications - two different applications signing in the same user will receive the same value in the oid claim. Thus, oid can be used when making queries to Microsoft online services, such as the Microsoft Graph. The Microsoft Graph will return this ID as the id property for a given user account. Because the oid allows multiple apps to correlate users, the profile scope is required in order to receive this claim. Note that if a single user exists in multiple tenants, the user will contain a different object ID in each tenant - they are considered different accounts, even though the user logs into each account with the same credentials.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.Plattform
member.summary: The plattform

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.Scope
member.summary: The set of scopes exposed by your application for which the client application has requested (and received) consent. Your app should verify that these scopes are valid ones exposed by your app, and make authorization decisions based on the value of these scopes. Only included for user tokens.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.SID
member.summary: In cases where the user has an on-premises authentication, this claim provides their SID. This can be used for authorization in legacy applications.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.SourceIPAddr
member.summary: The IP address the user authenticated from.

member.name: F:MSGraph.Core.JWTAccessTokenInfo.TenantID

For personal accounts, the value is 9188040d-6c67-4c5b-b112-36a304b66dad. The profile scope is required in order to receive this claim.

member.summary: Indicates that the token is a JWT.

member.summary: Only present in v1.0 tokens. Provides a human readable value that identifies the subject of the token. This value is not guaranteed to be unique within a tenant and should be used only for display purposes.

member.summary:
Team in MS Graph API
A team in Microsoft Teams is a collection of channel objects. A channel represents a topic, and therefore a logical isolation of discussion, within a team. Every team is associated with a group. The group has the same ID as the team.
